# Engineering Philosophy

**Design goals:** Priority is Safety, then Performance, then Developer Experience.

## Core Beliefs

### 1.1 Simplicity is a Feature (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Every line of code is a liability. The best code is code you didn't write.

❌ Bad: `class Service { func get() { return repo.get() } }` (unnecessary layer)
✅ Good: Delete unnecessary layers, prefer deletion over addition
⚠️ Why: Complexity kills maintainability, increases bugs, slows development
🔧 Fix: Fight complexity; delete code that doesn't add value
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 1.1 (Ghost Layer Prevention)

**Detect:** Unnecessary abstractions, wrapper classes, code that adds no value

---

### 1.1a Simplicity is the Hardest Revision

**CRITICAL:** Real simplicity comes from iteration and "throw one away," not from the first attempt.

❌ Bad: Shipping first draft as "simple", no revision passes, assuming simple = quick
✅ Good: Multiple passes to simplify; revise until design is minimal and clear
⚠️ Why: First attempt is rarely simplest; iteration reveals the super idea that solves axes together
🔧 Fix: Budget revision time; simplify after it works
📍 See: `engineering-philosophy.mdc` section 1.3 (Make it Work, Make it Right, Make it Fast)

**Detect:** One-pass "simple" solutions, no design revision, complexity defended as "good enough"

---

### 1.1b Zero Showstopper Policy

**CRITICAL:** Don't ship known critical bugs or unbounded risks; fix showstoppers before merge.

❌ Bad: Merging with known unbounded loops, unbounded queues, or critical correctness bugs "to fix later"
✅ Good: Bounded loops/queues, fail-fast on limits, fix showstoppers in design or implementation before merge
⚠️ Why: The second time may not transpire; shipping known critical debt undermines progress
🔧 Fix: Enforce bounded iteration and fail-fast; resolve critical issues before merge
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 2.4 (Bounded loops and queues)

**Detect:** Unbounded loops or queues, known critical bugs deferred, merge with "we'll fix later" on showstoppers

---

### 1.2 Boring Technology Wins (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Choose tools with decade-long track records over trendy alternatives.

❌ Bad: `import "github.com/new-hot-framework"` (trendy, unproven)
✅ Good: `import "net/http"` (standard library, battle-tested)
⚠️ Why: Let others discover edge cases; proven tech reduces risk
🔧 Fix: Prefer standard library, established tools, proven patterns
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 0.4 (Resume-Driven Development)

**Detect:** New frameworks for simple tasks, trendy databases, unproven tools

---

### 1.3 Make it Work, Make it Right, Make it Fast

**CRITICAL:** Optimization order: functionality first, correctness second, performance last.

❌ Bad: Premature optimization, complex solution before simple works
✅ Good: Get it running, clean it up, optimize with data
⚠️ Why: Premature optimization wastes time, adds complexity, optimizes wrong things
🔧 Fix: Measure first, optimize hot paths only, use data to guide decisions
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 0.3 (Hypothetical Futures)

**Detect:** Optimization before profiling, complex solutions for unproven needs

---

### 1.4 Agent-Optimized Design (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Design codebases for agent efficiency, not just human readability.

❌ Bad: Code structure optimized only for human navigation, unclear file organization, inconsistent patterns, non-standard layouts
✅ Good: Clear structure following conventions agents are trained on, consistent patterns, obvious file organization, standard project layouts (docs/, src/, tests/)
⚠️ Why: Agents work faster and more accurately when codebase follows predictable patterns they're trained on; fighting model conventions wastes tokens and time
🔧 Fix: Use standard project structures, consistent naming, clear separation of concerns, follow established patterns from training data
📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 9.1 (UI-First Development Anti-Pattern)

**Detect:** Unclear project structure, inconsistent patterns, files in unexpected locations, non-standard layouts, custom patterns requiring explanation

---

### 1.5 Core Logic-First Development (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Start new features by building core business logic/testable domain layer before UI/API layers.

❌ Bad: Building UI/API first, complex web interface before core logic works, UI tightly coupled to business logic, SwiftUI views before domain layer
✅ Good: Build core logic first (CLI, domain layer, or testable interfaces), verify logic works, then add UI/API layer, keep UI as thin layer over core
⚠️ Why: Core logic layer is faster to build/test, agents can verify output directly, reduces complexity, enables faster iteration, clearer separation of concerns
🔧 Fix: Always start with core logic/domain layer for new features; add UI/API only after logic is verified; for iOS/Swift: build Domain layer (Pure Swift) first, then Presentation layer (SwiftUI)

**Exception:** Pure UI apps with minimal business logic may iterate rapidly between UI and logic.

📍 See: `general-llm-anti-patterns.mdc` section 9.1, `swift-5-9-development-standards.mdc` section "Architectural Layers"

**Detect:** Building UI before core logic, complex interfaces before domain layer, skipping testable logic layer, business logic embedded in UI layer, SwiftUI views importing SwiftData/MusicKit directly

---

### 1.6 Continuous Refactoring (CRIT)

**CRITICAL:** Fix issues as they appear, don't defer to dedicated refactor days.

❌ Bad: Deferring refactoring to "later", accumulating technical debt, waiting for dedicated refactor days, "we'll fix this later" patterns
✅ Good: Fix issues immediately when noticed, refactor ad-hoc during development, address problems as they appear, refactor when prompts take too long
⚠️ Why: Prevents debt accumulation, keeps codebase clean, easier to fix when context is fresh, reduces future effort, poor code quality slows agent work
🔧 Fix: Address issues immediately when noticed, don't defer refactoring, fix problems during development, refactor when code quality impacts efficiency

**Refactoring Triggers:**
- Prompts taking longer than expected
- Seeing complex/ugly code in agent stream
- Code that confuses agents
- Patterns that slow down development

**Detect:** TODO comments for refactoring, deferred improvements, accumulating technical debt, ignoring agent inefficiency, waiting for dedicated refactor time

---

## Unix Philosophy

| Principle | Detect |
|-----------|--------|
| Do one thing well | Multiple responsibilities, God objects |
| Expect output to become input | Tight coupling, non-composable interfaces |
| Fail fast, fail loudly | Silent failures, generic error handling |
| Small is beautiful | Large files, complex modules |

